<font color="#FF0000">POSITION CLARIFICATION</font><br>
<tt>Sun Apr 20 15:02:12 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
What a hornets nest.  Originally Alias Lien, who is a 22 year old (I assume Vietnamese female) graduate student wanted to know what vets and non vets thought about her.  (Betty wisely asked if she came to the USA as an infant, older, circumstances - which really is important questions- in order to better understand her point of view). Later, Alias Lien said that she has had many negative interactions with men (I assume, repeat, assume, on the internet and off), and (my opinion) definately had a chip on her shoulder regarding men, and moi.  Her final comment that the former protester is now the most hostile voice on the thread, seems to be very odd.   All I did was ask her questions and she responded like I was stalking her. Sure some of my questions were loaded. Why not. I assume she was up to something deeper than Mary Kay Cosmetics after all. I assumed wrong it seemed.   <br><br>
I am sorry Alias Lien, but to continue any dialogue with you seems impossible. What to I think of you?  From what I know of you in the last 24 hours, I think you are bright, (22 and in grad school), yet have not learned any common sense.  I'm sorry that you have these issues that you seem to project on others. That's your problem and none of my business.  If that makes me hostile, well, it's a free w.w.w. world, and you can disconnect anytime.  You certainly seem to feel free in throwing electronic stones.  Why can't you catch a few in return?<br><br>
I think we all got off on this tangent because Alias Lien used words that are multi-sided, and then hit and ran, leaving us to pick up the pieces and slap each other with them. Betty and DocDel, thanks for your input and pointing out rough spots in my thinking. Feedback is such a wonderful thing, something that Alias Lien has apparently not come to terms with yet.<br><br>
For the record. I think every culture, religion, and ethnic group in America is welcome. They/we all have the right to their holidays, traditions, places of worship, and neighborhoods.  ALL.  But, America is like a giant chef's salad (the melting pot image doesn't work anymore I agree), and the overall &quot;taste&quot; of the salad is because all the pieces work together. While resentment-of-the-immigrant is also a natural (by history) American reaction, it is wrong, unfortunately, that won't make it go away.  <br><br>
However, when I knock multi-culturalism as dangerous to our country, it is because I see it pulling that salad bowl apart, and we become a bunch of veggies back in the produce section, with no bond holding us together. That mostly is, to me, in the need to hang extra I.D.'s, like Blank-American when describing one's self or another group.  <br><br>
The other issue is language. God Knows we have enough trouble here, just communicating ideas in English.  English is the language of America. I don't care what you speak at home, but in the business world, and the majority of the planet, English is the language.  The constitution of the USA was written in English, not French or Italian.  If we are going to print the ballot in Spanish and Vietnamese (which they do here in Southern California), then what about Cantonese, Mandrin, or the other 100+ Chinese dialects, let alone the other 100+mainstream languages?  I mean this gets absurd.  For logic sakes alone, we must all speak one tongue, at least in business and in public.<br><br>
I truly do not believe this is an issue of cultural pride, or being &quot;threatened&quot; of having &quot;the world as you know it&quot; (white man) shaken.  Hardly.  If you are secure with who you are, and where you have been, you can embrace anyone and everyone, and take the bits and pieces that you like and incorporate them into your own experience.  Isn't that the ideal?   {I love Japanese food but I can't stand Shushi. So I order the items I like (the combination dinners) and I don't sit at Shushi Bar's.  That's my choice, and the Resturant's choice and we co-exist just fine.  How does that threaten anyone?}<br><br>
Anyway, Alias Lien, if you want to post, do so, with or without your name, I don't care. If you don't want to read my thoughts, don't.  But, if you ask questions to ALL of the audience openly, than I have the right to respond, if I choose to.  If you want to call me names, and behave immaturely, that too is your right.  That is what America is all about.  If you tried this in China, or Viet Nam, or Saudi Arabia, or a few other countries, this minor freedom called Freedom of Speech just might become your death warrant.  Perhaps while you are studing &quot;re remembering&quot; you might just take a course in American History and Constitutional Law, and than kiss the ground you are standing on for your American Citizenship, and the lives of those that died to bring it to you. <br><br>
doc spatz <br><br>

